<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>get on one’s high horse • get on one’s horse</xh5><p> <i>get on one’s high horse</i>—(also: ride one’s high horse) become dignified and formal; assume an arrogant mien: As soon as I said a little slang to her she <u>got on her high horse</u>.</p><p> <i>get on one’s horse</i>—(sl.) hurry; start at once: You better <u>get on your horse</u> if you’re going to make that plane.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>be on the horse</b>—(Drug users) be under the effects of or addicted to heroin: How long have you <u>been on the horse</u>?</p> </entry>
